{"title_page": "\u00d3buda Synagogue", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n|building_name=\u00d3buda Synagogue\n|image=Budapest Obuda synagogue.jpg\n|caption=\n|map_type=Budapest\n|map_size=200\n|map_caption=Location within Budapest.\n|location=[[Budapest]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|47.536944|19.045833|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Orthodox Judaism]]\n|rite=[[Nusach Ari]]\n|functional_status=Active\n|leadership=Slomo K\u00f6ves\n|website=http://obudaizsinagoga.zsido.com/ {{in lang|hu}}\n|architect=Landherr Andr\u00e1s\n|architecture_type=[[Synagogue]]\n|architecture_style=[[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n|groundbreaking=1820\n|year_completed=July 20, 1821\n|consecration_year=\n|construction_cost=\n|specifications=no\n|capacity=\n|length=\n|width=\n|width_nave=\n|facade_direction=\n|height_max=\n|materials=\n}}\nThe '''\u00d3buda Synagogue''' is a [[synagogue]] built in [[\u00d3buda]], Hungary, in 1820\u20131821.\n\n==History==\n[[Jews]] settled in \u00d3buda, today a neighborhood of [[Budapest]], from c. 1712 at a time when Jews were forbidden to live in [[Buda]].<ref name=p155>Carole Herselle Krinsky, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uv1c0gkDgLsC Synagogues of Europe; Architecture, History, Meaning]'', MIT Press, 1985; revised edition, MIT Press, 1986 ({{ISBN|0486290786}}); Dover reprint, 1996, pp. 155\u2013156</ref><ref name=p41>{{cite book |title=Jewish Budapest Monuments, Rites and History, |author=Geza Komoroczy |author2=Viktoria Pusztai |author3=Andrea Strbik |author4=Kinga Frojimovics |publisher=Central European University Press |year=1999|isbn=963-9116-38-6 |page=41}}</ref> Countess [[Zichy]] invited them to live on Zichy family property in \u00d3buda. A synagogue was constructed in 1737.<ref name=p155/> The present building replaced it on the same site in 1820.<ref name=p155/> The building's original copper roof was requisitioned by the government and melted for munitions production during World War I.<ref name=p155/><ref>Hew Strachan, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zv8Zrrt6vqgC&dq=The+First+World+War:+To+Arms+2003&printsec=frontcover The First World War: To Arms, Hew Strachan]'', Oxford University Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-19-926191-1}}, p. 1048.</ref> The Jewish building had not been singled out; the [[Holy Trinity Cathedral, Sibiu]] was only one of the many churches that lost its bells as not only church bells but roofs, gutters, and even brass crucifixes were melted down across the Empire to produce copper for the war effort.<ref>Arthur James May, ''The Passing of the Hapsburg Monarchy, 1914\u20131918'', University of Pennsylvania Press, 1966, p. 336.</ref>\n\nAt the time the synagogue was built, the community of \u00d3buda was the largest Jewish community in Hungary.<ref name=p41/> \n\nAccording to the boastful author of an 1822 Austro-Hungarian guidebook, not only was the synagogue the \"most magnificent\" new building in \u00d3buda, few synagogues elsewhere could compare to its magnificence. It was \"undoubtedly\" one of the most magnificent synagogues in the entire [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]], and one of the finest in all Europe, \"Not even the Jewish temple of [[Timi\u0219oara|Temesv\u00e1r]] can compete with it in pomp, not to mention the [[Old New Synagogue|old synagogues]] of [[Prague]]. The only building that may outdo it in grandiosity is the building of the Jewish community of [[Amsterdam]],\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Jewish Budapest Monuments, Rites and History, |author=Geza Komoroczy |author2=Viktoria Pusztai |author3=Andrea Strbik |author4=Kinga Frojimovics |publisher=Central European University Press |year=1999|isbn=963-9116-38-6 |page=46}}</ref> (a reference to the [[Portuguese Synagogue (Amsterdam)|Portuguese Synagogue]] in Amsterdam).\n\nIn 1831, following the death of Rabbi Moses Munz, the congregation left orthodoxy to follow reformist [[Neolog Judaism]].<ref name=p155/>\n\nBeginning in 1848, the congregation expressed its support for Hungarian nationalism by having sermons delivered every other week in Hungarian.<ref name=p155/>\nIn 1850, the town had 3439 Jewish residents, 31.4% of the population.\n\nThe community shrank throughout the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries as members moved into the flourishing city of [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]].<ref name=p155/> But the town, district III of Budapest was still 10% Jewish in 1926. In the 1970s, the diminished Jewish community sold the building for use as a television studio.<ref name=p155/>\n\nUsed for a long time as a TV studio, it was reinaugurated as a synagogue on September 5, 2010, [[Yona Metzger]], chief rabbi of Israel and [[Zsolt Semj\u00e9n]], Hungarian vice-prime minister, being present.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}Jean Vidal; \"Juda\u00efsme et Isra\u00ebl \u00e0 Budapest\" in ''L'Arche'', n\u00b0 629, October 2010</ref> The new rabbi is Slomo K\u00f6ves, a [[Lubavitch]].\n\n==Architecture==\nThe synagogue was designed in French [[Empire style]] by architect [[Andreas Landesherr]], who greatly enlarged and embellished the 1731 building, altering the appearance beyond recognition.<ref>{{cite book |title=Jewish Budapest Monuments, Rites and History, |author=Geza Komoroczy |author2=Viktoria Pusztai |author3=Andrea Strbik |author4=Kinga Frojimovics |publisher=Central European University Press |year=1999|isbn=963-9116-38-6 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> The [[pediment]] and six [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]] columns of the facade give the synagogue the aspect of a classical temple. The pediment was embellished with carved Classical ornament, and surmounted by the tablets of the Ten Commandments.<ref name=p180>Rachel Wischnitzer, ''Architecture of the European Synagogue'', Jewish Publication Society of America, 1964, p. 180\u2013181</ref> On the side walls two tiers of round-arched windows alternate with classical [[pilaster]]s.<ref name=p155/>\n\nInside, the [[Bema#Judaism|bimah]] boasted four impressive corner columns in the form of the then popular [[Egyptian Revival architecture|Egyptian Revival]] obelisks. Each [[obelisk]] stood atop a [[plinth]], both heavily embellished with carved, classical ornament, capped by a sphere capped by an eagle. The [[Torah ark]] was flanked by classical columns, and topped by Tablets of the Law, surmounted by a crown and surrounded by a painted burst of clouds.<ref name=p180/> It once held no fewer than 28 [[Torah]] scrolls belonging to the wealthy congregation.<ref name=p155/> The women's gallery ran along the northern and western walls. Fourteen chandeliers hung from the ceiling, causing some congregants to complain about the extravagance of the synagogue's directors.<ref>''Jewish Budapest; Monuments, Rites and History'', by Geza Komoroczy, Viktoria Pusztai, Andrea Strbik, Kinga Frojimovics, Central European University Press (January 1999), p. 45\u201346.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obuda Synagogue}}\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish culture in Europe]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi synagogues]]\n[[Category:\u00d3buda]]\n[[Category:Orthodox synagogues]]\n[[Category:Regency and Biedermeier synagogues]]\n[[Category:Synagogues completed in 1821]]\n[[Category:Synagogues in Budapest]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n|building_name=\u00d3buda Synagogue\n|image=Budapest Obuda synagogue.jpg\n|caption=\n|map_type=Budapest\n|map_size=200\n|map_caption=Location within Budapest.\n|location=[[Budapest]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|47.536944|19.045833|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Orthodox Judaism]]\n|rite=[[Nusach Ari]]\n|functional_status=Active\n|leadership=Slomo K\u00f6ves\n|website=http://obudaizsinagoga.zsido.com/ {{in lang|hu}}\n|architect=Landherr Andr\u00e1s\n|architecture_type=[[Synagogue]]\n|architecture_style=[[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n|groundbreaking=1820\n|year_completed=July 20, 1821\n|consecration_year=\n|construction_cost=\n|specifications=no\n|capacity=\n|length=\n|width=\n|width_nave=\n|facade_direction=\n|height_max=\n|materials=\n}}\nThe '''\u00d3buda Synagogue''' is a [[synagogue]] built in [[\u00d3buda]], Hungary, in 1820\u20131821.\n\n==History==\n[[Jews]] settled in \u00d3buda, today a neighborhood of [[Budapest]], from c. 1712 at a time when Jews were forbidden to live in [[Buda]].<ref name=p155>Carole Herselle Krinsky, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uv1c0gkDgLsC Synagogues of Europe; Architecture, History, Meaning]'', MIT Press, 1985; revised edition, MIT Press, 1986 ({{ISBN|0486290786}}); Dover reprint, 1996, pp. 155\u2013156</ref><ref name=p41>{{cite book |title=Jewish Budapest Monuments, Rites and History, |author=Geza Komoroczy |author2=Viktoria Pusztai |author3=Andrea Strbik |author4=Kinga Frojimovics |publisher=Central European University Press |year=1999|isbn=963-9116-38-6 |page=41}}</ref> Countess [[Zichy]] invited them to live on Zichy family property in \u00d3buda. A synagogue was constructed in 1737.<ref name=p155/> The present building replaced it on the same site in 1820.<ref name=p155/> The building's original copper roof was requisitioned by the government and melted for munitions production during World War I.<ref name=p155/><ref>Hew Strachan, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zv8Zrrt6vqgC&dq=The+First+World+War:+To+Arms+2003&printsec=frontcover The First World War: To Arms, Hew Strachan]'', Oxford University Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-19-926191-1}}, p. 1048.</ref> The Jewish building had not been singled out; the [[Holy Trinity Cathedral, Sibiu]] was only one of the many churches that lost its bells as not only church bells but roofs, gutters, and even brass crucifixes were melted down across the Empire to produce copper for the war effort.<ref>Arthur James May, ''The Passing of the Hapsburg Monarchy, 1914\u20131918'', University of Pennsylvania Press, 1966, p. 336.</ref>\n\nAt the time the synagogue was built, the community of \u00d3buda was the largest Jewish community in Hungary.<ref name=p41/> \n\nAccording to the boastful author of an 1822 Austro-Hungarian guidebook, not only was the synagogue the \"most magnificent\" new building in \u00d3buda, few synagogues elsewhere could compare to its magnificence. It was \"undoubtedly\" one of the most magnificent synagogues in the entire [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]], and one of the finest in all Europe, \"Not even the Jewish temple of [[Timi\u015foara|Temesv\u00e1r]] can compete with it in pomp, not to mention the [[Old New Synagogue|old synagogues]] of [[Prague]]. The only building that may outdo it in grandiosity is the building of the Jewish community of [[Amsterdam]],\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Jewish Budapest Monuments, Rites and History, |author=Geza Komoroczy |author2=Viktoria Pusztai |author3=Andrea Strbik |author4=Kinga Frojimovics |publisher=Central European University Press |year=1999|isbn=963-9116-38-6 |page=46}}</ref> (a reference to the [[Portuguese Synagogue (Amsterdam)|Portuguese Synagogue]] in Amsterdam).\n\nIn 1831, following the death of Rabbi Moses Munz, the congregation left orthodoxy to follow reformist [[Neolog Judaism]].<ref name=p155/>\n\nBeginning in 1848, the congregation expressed its support for Hungarian nationalism by having sermons delivered every other week in Hungarian.<ref name=p155/>\nIn 1850, the town had 3439 Jewish residents, 31.4% of the population.\n\nThe community shrank throughout the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries as members moved into the flourishing city of [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]].<ref name=p155/> But the town, district III of Budapest was still 10% Jewish in 1926. In the 1970s, the diminished Jewish community sold the building for use as a television studio.<ref name=p155/>\n\nUsed for a long time as a TV studio, it was reinaugurated as a synagogue on September 5, 2010, [[Yona Metzger]], chief rabbi of Israel and [[Zsolt Semj\u00e9n]], Hungarian vice-prime minister, being present.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}Jean Vidal; \"Juda\u00efsme et Isra\u00ebl \u00e0 Budapest\" in ''L'Arche'', n\u00b0 629, October 2010</ref> The